comments.message: Would it be better to handle the ARM64LINARO flag up here? Otherwise there is risk of these two definitions diverging over time.

The line is duplicated at line 20 just because we want to remove -lz before it is fully supported.
Ok sounds good. I had talked to Kaiyu last week about potentially using the RockPro to compile an arm-compatible zlib.dll
Rather than installing from linaro.org, we can do apt-get install g++-aarch64-linux-gnu.

make clean linux64/swicwe linux32/swicwe aarch64/swicwe win64/swicwe win32/swicwe

Resolves: FWTOOLS-353

comments.message: Please use upper case to silence the Quality-Check
At line 2316, we're passing in searchbufp=bufp=offset+BC_HEADER_SIZE. So why are we adding offset+BC_HEADER_SIZE here?
Same comment. Looks like this change is not needed. This function looks OK and it is copied from FW code. Just the calling parameters at line 2316 need to be updated.

Because, the loop body wants to load and examine a BC_HEADER_SIZE sized range of the buffer starting at bufp.

It looks like search_and_count_cweimage adds BC_HEADER_SIZE to avoid searching the master header at the base of the buffer. (But was neglecting to subtract that from the size.) With this loop fix alone, I was still getting a segfault because of that missing subtraction.

I think the original do loop will work with the fixes in search_and_count_cweimage, under the assumption that there are initially enough bytes starting at bufp to load the initial header, and the size fields in all the headers that are encountered are correct.

The way we have it now, it will guard against a corrupt situation where there is less than a header starting at bufp, or a bad size field in one of the headers which increments bufp to a place in the buffer that is too close to the end to load another header.

I suppose we could add a sanity check that after this loop, bufp should be at *exactly* the end of the data (one byte past), not just too close to the end to fetch another header.

Actually, since all this change really does is make it more robust, it doesn't go far enough. A corrupt size field could actually cause pointer wraparound! So that bufp ends up pointing below searchbufp. (And anyway, comparing pointers *after* the out of bounds increment is undefined behavior; you have to do the checks in the original arithmetic.)

Alas, this is inconsistent; we use BC_HEADER_SIZE in some places and this sizeof in other places. If these two are the same, then this increment is safe to do, precisely because we only execute the while body if we have room to do this header-sized increment.

Okay, so here, basically what we want to check is this condition:

   // is the buffer really at least as big as the size
   searchbufp + searchbuflen - bufp <= temphdr.bcImageSize

if so, then it's safe to do the bufp increment, otherwise we should bail.
We should calculate the displaced offset and trimmed size, rather than repeating these calculations in numerous lines.
What about these and the other ones at line 3855, 3964, 4005?

That looks wrong also. I think this code is not involved in the catenate feature though.

Of course, this is potentially affected by changes in blSearchCWEImage; good reason to put all this work into that special branch where it supposed to go.
yes, these all looks wrong and need to be updated.

I noticed that all the calls to this function skip the base image header. So I just took that out from those callers and make this function do it. The function takes a pointer to the entire image, and does that header skipping internally.
This way, the condition is easy to understand: while we have at least a header-sized chunk between here and the end, let's analyze.

Oops, this is not quite strong enough. Here is the question: are the sub-images four-byte-aligned (or more strictly?) Of course they must be.  So what if a size is like 0x12345? We end up with a misaligned bufp.  How we can handle that is 1) treat a misaligned size as the image being junk and return NULL; or 2) round up the size to the four-byte alignment and keep going.
the images are not aligned that is why the header has to be stored into tmphdr so that int can be accessible from tmphdr (not from image itself)

Gotcha.

Hmm, the compiler I'm using (ubuntu 18.04's g++) doesn't issue the signed/unsigned warning for this for some reason, but for 1611 it did.

I will roll back patch set #3 where I added the alignment check.

commits.commitMessage:
FWTOOLS-223 - spkgtool: extract components from spkg/cwe file

Issue Description:
As part of delta update, it is needed to extract images individual images(e.g. modem, legato, rootfs etc) from spkg. The tool should also support to extract the cwe headers and corresponding squashfs/ubi image.
However, currently no tool can reliably do this. Existing spkgtool seems broken.

Root Cause:
Current swicwe tool does not support extraction of images from SPKG (BOOT, MODEM, APPL, FILE, FOTO).
This update adds extra feature to the tool to allow extraction of components.

Solution:
Add additional functions (split_spkg_level_1 and split_spkg_level_2) to main.cpp
Also adds another function to generate the appropriate output file name (generate_split_file_name).

Limitations:
For image type FOTO and FILE, the level 2 splitting algorithm only extracts them into top level components.

Resolves: FWTOOLS-223
Related: FWTOOLS-164

Signed-off-by: Leo Liu <Leliu@sierrawireless.com>

comments.message: When built from a 32bit linux, this would end up in linux64/ while it's really a 32bit binary.

After the build could you copy the $(BIN64DIR)/swicwe to ./swicwe ?

Also this doesn't generate a swicwe32 binary so the target would always rebuild.
Also, after the build could you copy the $(BIN32DIR)/swicwe to ./swicwe32 ?

There is some duplication of code here so I would propose something else.
The idea is that even if the host can't cross compile (and eventually it might not need to), the simple build should still be fine

This might be easier to allow build on other platforms as well (Windows ? Unix ? ARM ?)

BINDIR := linux
MACHINE := $(shell uname -m)
VERSION_NUMBER ?= $(shell git describe --tags)
CXXFLAGS := -DVERSION_NUMBER='"$(VERSION_NUMBER)"' -Wall -Werror -m32 -DEXTERN_MAIN -lz

all: swicwe

$(BINDIR):
	mkdir $(BINDIR)

swicwe: hdrcnv.cpp main.cpp cwezip.cpp fotapkghdrcat.cpp common.cpp | $(BINDIR)
	${CXX} $^ $(CXXFLAGS) -o $(BINDIR)/swicwe

## Allow cross compilation for 32-bit
ifeq ($(MACHINE), x86_64)

BIN32DIR := linux32

$(BIN32DIR):
	mkdir $(BIN32DIR)

swicwe32: hdrcnv.cpp main.cpp cwezip.cpp fotapkghdrcat.cpp common.cpp | $(BIN32DIR)
	${CXX} $^ $(CXXFLAGS) -o $(BIN32DIR)/swicwe
	cp $(BIN32DIR)/swicwe ./swicwe32

install32: swicwe32
	cp swicwe32 /usr/local/bin

endif

clean:
	rm -rf $(BINDIR) $(BIN32DIR) swicwe swicwe32

The goal is to have a clear 64 and 32 bit executable, with the same name. If you build this on a 32 bit machine linux/swicwe will be 32 bit, or on a 64 and linux/swicwe will be 64 bit (assuming you didn't meant o inlcude -m32 in all builds). This ambiguity defeats what we are trying to achieve, IMO. I will however try to implement some of the useful consolidation found here.

I see, I was trying to achieve the opposite here, ie having a swicwe exe that is compatible with the machine were it is being built, no matter the architecture.

I hadn't seen that the swicwe was copied as swicwe32 in the i386 case, which makes your make target invalid (swicwe target produces a swicwe32 executable.

I updated my proposition accordingly.
Also, I'm using getconf LONG_BIT instead of uname -m as the latter is probably not a good switch (I'm not sure that it returns i386 on all 32-bit linux).

VERSION_NUMBER ?= $(shell git describe --tags)

	mkdir $(BINDIR)

	${CXX} $^ $(CXXFLAGS) -o $(BINDIR)/swicwe

install: $(SWICWE_BIN)

## Allow cross compilation for 32-bit from 64-bit machines
ifeq ($(ARCH), 64)

BIN32DIR := linux32

$(BIN32DIR):
	mkdir $(BIN32DIR)

swicwe32: hdrcnv.cpp main.cpp cwezip.cpp fotapkghdrcat.cpp common.cpp | $(BIN32DIR)
	${CXX} $^ $(CXXFLAGS) -m32 -o $(BIN32DIR)/swicwe
	cp $(BIN32DIR)/swicwe ./swicwe32

install32: swicwe32

endif

clean:
	rm -rf $(BINDIR) $(BIN32DIR) swicwe swicwe32

You can potentially have a common clean and do something like:

 clean:
    rm -r $(BIN64DIR) $(BIN32DIR) swicwe*

Here you can use swicwe:

 cp swicwe /usr/local/bin

Here you can use swicwe32:

 cp swicwe32 /usr/local/bin
the idea is for swicwe to be the only executable name. swicwe32 can be used if needed but install should use the swicwe executable.

In that case you can do
